\]

The excess base is titrated with HCl:

\[
n_{\text{HCl}} = 0.0236\;\text{L}\times 0.0108\;\text{mol L}^{-1}=2.5488\times10^{-4}\;\text{mol}
\]

Since \(\ce{Ba(OH)2 + 2 HCl -> BaCl2 + 2 H2O}\),

\[
n_{\text{Ba(OH)$_2$, excess}} = \frac{n_{\text{HCl}}}{2}=1.2744\times10^{-4}\;\text{mol}
\]

Thus the moles of \(\ce{Ba(OH)2}\) that reacted with \(\ce{CO2}\) (and therefore the moles of \(\ce{CO2}\) in the air sample) are  

\[
n_{\ce{CO2}} = n_{\text{Ba(OH)$_2$, i}}-n_{\text{Ba(OH)$_2$, excess}}
           = 5.80\times10^{-4}-1.2744\times10^{-4}
           = 4.5256\times10^{-4}\;\text{mol}
\]

Mass of \(\ce{CO2}\):

\[
m_{\ce{CO2}} = n_{\ce{CO2}}\times M_{\ce{CO2}}
             = 4.5256\times10^{-4}\;\text{mol}\times 44.01\;\text{g mol}^{-1}
             = 1.99\times10^{-2}\;\text{g}
\]

Using the given density of \(\ce{CO2}\) (\(1.98\;\text{g L}^{-1}\)) the volume of \(\ce{CO2}\) at the same conditions is  

\[
V_{\ce{CO2}} = \frac{m_{\ce{CO2}}}{\rho_{\ce{CO2}}}
             = \frac{1.99\times10^{-2}\;\text{g}}{1.98\;\text{g L}^{-1}}
             = 1.01\times10^{-2}\;\text{L}=10.1\;\text{mL}
\]

The air sample volume is \(3.00\;\text{L}=3000\;\text{mL}\).  
Hence the concentration of \(\ce{CO2}\) in ppm (mL \(\ce{CO2}\) per \(10^{6}\) mL air) is  

\[
\text{ppm}= \frac{V_{\ce{CO2}}}{V_{\text{air}}}\times10^{6}
           = \frac{10.1}{3000}\times10^{6}
           = 3.35\times10^{3}
\]

\[
\boxed{3.35\times10^{3}}\ \text{ppm}
\]"""

Model's final answer: 3.35x10^{3}

Correct answer: 3350.0

